[normal]Written evidence submitted by Dr Robin Curtis (HOT48)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Most of my comments are related to the use of heat in buildings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat ene
[normal]rgy demand?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Qualitatively - yes. Quantitatively - probably not. In terms of heat loss from buildings the rumoured relaxation of Part L of the Building Standards is unhelpful. The construction and testing of new buildings to meet the current Part L require
[normal]ments is not of sufficient rigour to ensure that the completed buildings meet the design heat loss levels. Insulation and draught proofing that will last the lifetime of a building are the most cost effective way of reducing a building
[normal]'
[normal]s heat demand. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It 
[normal]is acknowledged that there are still far too many UK households where there has been a failure to install loft and/or cavity wall insulation, and draught stripping measures. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Any learning from the recent Retrofit for the Future programme should be evaluat
[normal]ed and disseminated.  The most cost effective measures in terms of heat and carbon reduction should be rolled out as soon as possible. Significant carbon reductions were achieved in many of the properties. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The use of night storage heating should be re-ex
[normal]amined. It was introduced in a different era to provide for baseload operation of nuclear stations. However, it leads to a wastage of heat, increased energy usage, and when driven by fossil fuel electricity, higher carbon emissions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst this document 
[normal]speaks to heat demand reduction - there is minimal referenc
[normal]e to waste heat elimination and
[normal]/or recovery. Greater attention should be given to the possible use of all varieties of heat pumps to deliver waste heat recovery in industrial processes. 
[normal]Encourag
[normal]e
[normal]me
[normal]nt should be given to the use 
[normal]of newer low temperature heat-to-electric
[normal]ity devices, and planners should
[normal] be encouraged to prom
[normal]o
[normal]te t
[normal]he use of cascaded waste heat utilisation either from power stations and/or industrial process plant. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
