[normal]Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent 
[normal]an accurate picture?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Everything!
[normal] There must be a true reflection of the lifetime carbon emissions associated with the use of biomass as a heating fuel.
[normal] I currently have difficulty with 
[normal]figures reported by DEFRA, DECC and the Carbon Trust. The current Carb
[normal]on Trust guidelines f
[normal]or different methods of heating
[normal] buildings attribute a very low carbon value to biomass.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition the dynamics / lifetime of the carbon cycle needs to be accounted for. We sh
[normal]ould only be burning biomass fro
[normal]m alre
[normal]ady sustainable 
[normal]sources. Ideally, given the currently dangerous levels of CO2 in the atmosphere, biomass carbon emitted in year one, should be re
[normal]-
[normal]absorbed by new biomass in a
[normal] matter of years - not decades.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go f
[normal]ar enough?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]See previous paragraph.
