[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]At current tariff 
[normal]levels, efficient mains gas boilers can offer some of the lowest running costs for the delivery of heat - particularly in older buildings (compared to say heat pumps). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How likely this will last depends on future UK gas prices and availability. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The enor
[normal]mous, past, investment in the availability and capacity of the UK gas grid, means that it is currently able to handle peak winter heating demands (as long as there is sufficient supply and storage capacity). However, gas has little to offer in terms of 
[normal]fut
[normal]ure 
[normal]carbon reduction, until and if 
[normal]carbon neutral 
[normal]biogas becomes widely available. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given the investment in the U
[normal]K gas grid, encouragement could
[normal] be given to the development
[normal] and roll out
[normal] of gas fired, domestic
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]air and ground source heat pumps. These offer some reduction in gas consumption and carbon emissions - and may be one of the 
[normal]interim 
[normal]solutions for high density urban housing. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Note that DECC's objective of combining electrically driven heat pumps with progressively lower carbon electricity leads to the ultimate decarbonisation of 
[normal]heat - and the release of invalua
[normal]ble liquid and gaseous fuels for far better utilisation than the pr
[normal]ov
[normal]ision of heat, ie
[normal]/eg process industry, feedstock, and transportation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]  •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A long story. We do not have a cultural history of using community heating. There are all sorts of development barriers
[normal]. An example in Cornwall is where there is the opportunity for the development of one of Europe's largest minewater heating systems in the Camborne/Pool/Redruth Redevelopment Scheme.  It will not be realised because there is no fin
[normal]ancing or structural capa
[normal]bility within the municipal
[normal]ity/ scheme developer to install the infrastructure. Development plots will be let to individual commercial developers - who will not be prepared to finance/install/develop the communal infrastructure. There are various in
[normal]stituti
[normal]onal barriers as well. I
[normal]n a totally free energy market,
[normal] the developer cannot guarantee uptake of the heating supply by future occupiers. It is now an issue on the Southampton District heating scheme - where new occupiers are questioning whether they have t
[normal]o and/or will make use of the communal distr
[normal]ict heating /cooling scheme.  Th
[normal]e widespread adoption of community heating schem
[normal]e
[normal]s in countries in Europe us
[normal]ual arises through the participa
[normal]tion of the "municipality" as the developer / owner. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is interesting to note that in Sweden, with a history of municipality developed heating schemes, the recent privatisation is apparently leading to the dismantling of some schemes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Another issue is that the lack of recent installations in the UK means 
[normal]that there is a dearth of information regarding the true installed costs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] •
