[normal]  •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Should the government take any further any specif
[normal]ic actions in relation to cooling?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It should encourage the adoption of high efficiency cooling technology, and the use of passive cooling whenever possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In considering the energy use and carbon emissions of buildings, thought should be given to the f
[normal]act that highly insulated buildings now give rise to cooling demand in. (Many new office buildings in the UK are now cooling 
[normal]dominated). The objective is not necessarily to prevent the use of cooling - the objective should be to minimise the overall use of
[normal] energy, and reduce the overall carbon emissions, over the whole year comfort cycle. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]  •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I am not sure how yo
[normal]u have come to this conclusion. 
[normal]It has taken 
[normal]almost 
[normal]four years for the RHI to come
[normal] 
[normal]to pass - and is only now being
[normal] offered in any seriousness (Still yet to happen in anger - ie next Spring (perhaps?)
[normal])
[normal]. This has caused utter mayhem in the supply industry and amongst consumers. Time will only tell whether the almost agreed levels of RHI t
[normal]ariff will now lead to great
[normal]er
[normal] heat pump rollout. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the non-domestic sector it should be bore in mind that the gestation period for a new building can be anywhere between 1 and 5 years - it is not a case of just retro-fitting a few so
[normal]lar panels to a bui
[normal]lding.  Given
[normal] that there is still no pre-approval process for non-do
[normal]mestic RHI
[normal], it will be interesting to see whether the availability of a possible RHI tariff once the building has been
[normal] constructed and commissioned 
[normal]will induce developers to commit to 
[normal]renewable heat technologies - let alone heat pumps. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]  •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Who knows !
[normal] It will take some time for the supply industry to put together the trained personnel to deliver in significant numbers and to the newly required MCS standards.  Quite how the customers will react to the offer of RHI is impossible to gauge. Given the respo
[normal]nse to FIT, 
[normal]it will all depend on the percei
[normal]ved attractivenes
[normal]s of the offering. It should al
[normal]s
[normal]o
[normal] be appreciated that the replacement of a heating system is significantly more complex than the installation of say, PV panels.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] •
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thermal storage is a potential
[normal] useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is funding a few possible thermal storage technologies through the DECC Ene
[normal]rgy Entrepreneurs Schemes and the DECC Thermal Storage Innovation Scheme. The perception that mass installation of electrically driven heat pumps will give rise to peaking problems on the U grid means that attention should be given to innovations that can 
[normal]smooth out peak heating demand.  Once the current hiatus over the use of ground source thermal storage schemes for non-domestic heating and cooling is overcome, we should see greater adoption of this technology - which has been stalled for the last four ye
[normal]ars.  Increased attention should be paid to long lasting, cost effective
[normal],
[normal] phase change materials. 
[normal]September 2013
